My retirement simulator is designed to give you a sense of how much you can spend in retirement and how long your funds may last (depending on when you retire, how much you draw out of your superannuation each year, and how your funds are invested). It is intended as an educational tool, helping you see the long-term effects of your retirement choices on the things you can control that can really make a difference, such as:

  • your retirement age and the impact of retiring sooner or later;
  • changing the income that you draw during retirement;
  • changing your investment mix;
  • investments being held inside vs outside of superannuation; and
  • making extra contributions, either via regular salary sacrifice, or personal contributions either as regular or as a one-off lump sum

However, My retirement simulator is a financial model and, as such, cannot accurately predict your end super balance or the effects of drawing an income from your retirement savings. This will depend on a range of matters we cannot take into account, including (but not limited to):

  • Changes to your personal circumstances. Unexpected things tend to happen in life. For example:
    • You may decide, or find you need, to take time out of the work force. As a model, My retirement simulator cannot predict or take account of your individual situation and assumes you make steady, predictable contributions to your super over time.
    • You may decide to draw more or less income from your retirement savings, or need to make large cash withdrawals from your account to cover unexpected costs such as medical expenses, gifts, etc. As a model, My retirement simulator cannot predict or take account of your individual situation and assumes you receive steady, predictable income payments from your allocated pension over time.
  • Unpredictable external factors beyond your control, such as changes to investment earnings, tax and inflation. My retirement simulator assumes these will operate at set, steady rates over your working life. Although this may seem somewhat simplistic, these assumptions are essential to allow the simulator to demonstrate the effect of things you can control, and to illustrate the difference this can make.
